Somaliaâ€™s government and regional
officials are discussing plans to create an autonomous region on
the border with  Kenya  to stabilize an area currently controlled
by the al-Shabaab militia, the Standard reported.  The Somali administrative regions of Gedo, Lower Juba and
Middle Juba may be incorporated into a region known as Jubaland,
the Nairobi-based newspaper said, citing Mohamed Mohamed, the
coordinator of the initiative.  Somali lawmakers, officials from the  African Union , the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development and regional elders
are discussing the plan at a seven-day meeting in Nairobi, the
newspaper said.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
